#: src\concepts/contract-vs-endpoints.md:11
msgid "The contract"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-vs-endpoints.md:13
msgid ""
"`schema.sahou.yaml` is the one file that defines _what_ the system "
"communicates: the nodes, the messages, and the connections between them. It "
"is transport- and environment-independent. This is the file you version, "
"review, and share."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-vs-endpoints.md:17
msgid "The endpoints"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-vs-endpoints.md:19
msgid ""
"`endpoints.<env>.yaml` says _which machine plays which node_ and carries any "
"environment-specific settings, so the **same contract runs unchanged across "
"environments** (dev, staging, an installation on site). It is deliberately "
"small — often just a namespace — because **LAN auto-discovery is the "
"default**:"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-vs-endpoints.md:30
msgid ""
"When you omit endpoints entirely, Sahou uses the LAN-auto default (namespace "
"`sahou`)."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-vs-endpoints.md:33
msgid "Why the split matters"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-vs-endpoints.md:35
msgid ""
"Because deployment lives outside the contract, moving from your laptop to a "
"gallery network, or from one machine to three, does not touch the contract. "
"You change _where_ nodes run without changing _what_ they say. See "
"[Networking & deployment](../networking-and-deployment.md) for how discovery "
"and transport use these files."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/ir-and-round-trip.md:3
msgid ""
"At the center of Sahou is a neutral data model called the **IR** "
"(intermediate representation). The surface you write (YAML) is never wired "
"directly to the output (codegen, transport, the GUI). The IR always sits in "
"between."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/ir-and-round-trip.md:15
msgid "Why an IR"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/ir-and-round-trip.md:17
msgid ""
"Wiring surface syntax straight to output couples the two: every consumer "
"would have to re-parse YAML and re-implement validation, and they would "
"drift. With the IR as the single neutral model, parsing, validation, and "
"every output share one source of truth. The CLI, the browser GUI, and the "
"language runtimes all consume the same IR."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/ir-and-round-trip.md:23
msgid "The three properties the core guarantees"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/ir-and-round-trip.md:25
msgid ""
"The core (`sahou-core`, written in Rust and WASM-capable) keeps three "
"properties so the same logic can back a CLI, a browser GUI, and future "
"tooling:"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/ir-and-round-trip.md:28
msgid ""
"**Parse _and_ serialize** — reading a contract into the IR and writing it "
"back out is round-trip stable. (Comments are the one known exception; `sahou "
"fmt` notes this.)"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/ir-and-round-trip.md:31
msgid ""
"**Structured diagnostics** — validation returns positional, structured "
"results: a `code`, a `path` to the exact location, and a `message`. Not a "
"single opaque error string. See [Say NO early](say-no-early.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/ir-and-round-trip.md:34
msgid ""
"**Pure and WASM-capable** — parse / serialize / validate are pure functions "
"with no I/O, so they run identically in the CLI and in the browser (the GUI "
"runs the core compiled to WebAssembly)."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/ir-and-round-trip.md:38
msgid ""
"Everything under `gen/` — `descriptor.json` (the full IR) and any typed "
"stubs — is produced from the IR by `sahou gen`. Treat it as generated "
"output; edit the contract, not `gen/`."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:3
msgid ""
"The core idea of Sahou: a wrong type or a mistyped field should be rejected "
"**the moment it crosses the boundary** — and, with generated type stubs, "
"**in your editor at build time** — rather than failing later, somewhere far "
"away, in the hardest place to debug."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:8
msgid "Two boundaries where NO happens"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:10
msgid ""
"**At build time, in your editor (opt-in).** Generate a typed stub with "
"`sahou gen --lang <python|ts>` and your editor type-checks the messages a "
"node sends and receives before anything runs. This is the earliest possible "
"NO."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:13
msgid ""
"**At runtime, at the boundary.** When a message is sent or received, the "
"core validates it against the contract. A send-boundary rejection raises an "
"error (`SahouRejected`); a receive-boundary rejection is routed to a reject "
"handler, never to your message handler. Either way the bad value does not "
"propagate."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:18
msgid "Never silently fold the contract"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:20
msgid ""
"Sahou refuses the quiet failure modes that serde-style parsing defaults to:"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:22
msgid "**Duplicate keys** are rejected, not silently resolved \"last one wins\"."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:23
msgid "**Unknown keys** (typos) are rejected, not silently dropped."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:25
msgid ""
"This is enforced with `deny_unknown_fields` and unique-map checks. A typo in "
"a field name is a boundary NO, not a field that silently vanishes."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:28
msgid "Structured diagnostics"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:30
msgid ""
"`sahou validate` returns a list of `{ code, path, message }` — each pointing "
"at the exact place. A few common codes:"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:33 src\schema-authoring.md:118
msgid "code"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:33 src\schema-authoring.md:118
msgid "meaning"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:35 src\schema-authoring.md:121
msgid "`unknown_node`"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:35
msgid "`from`/`to` references an identifier not in `nodes`"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:36 src\schema-authoring.md:122
msgid "`self_loop`"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:36
msgid "`from` and `to` are the same node"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:37
msgid "`missing_slot` / `unexpected_slot`"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:37
msgid "slots don't match the `pattern`"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:38 src\schema-authoring.md:126
msgid "`duplicate_field`"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:38 src\schema-authoring.md:126
msgid "a field name repeats within one slot"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:39 src\schema-authoring.md:130
msgid "`missing_items`"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:39
msgid "`array`/`map` omitted its element/value type"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:40 src\schema-authoring.md:132
msgid "`invalid_default`"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:40 src\schema-authoring.md:132
msgid "a `default` violates its own type/constraints"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:42
msgid "The full list is in [Schema authoring](../schema-authoring.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:44
msgid "Runtime interprets the IR; stubs are opt-in"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/say-no-early.md:46
msgid ""
"At runtime, the engine plus its interpretation of the IR does the validation "
"— so the boundary NO exists whether or not you generated stubs. Static types "
"are an **opt-in, consumer-side** convenience layer; the engine never reads "
"them. Because a stub is generated and code drifts, `sahou check` compares a "
"stub against the current IR and rejects on drift — a natural CI gate."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-evolution.md:3
msgid ""
"Contracts change. A node gains a field; a new receiver is added; a message "
"grows. Sahou decides, per connection, whether a change is safe to roll out "
"while peers are still running."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-evolution.md:7
msgid "Additive passes, breaking is a NO"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-evolution.md:9
msgid "Compatibility is judged **per connection** and **structurally**:"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-evolution.md:11
msgid ""
"**Additive changes pass.** Adding an optional field, or otherwise widening "
"in a structurally-compatible way, is allowed — old and new peers can coexist."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-evolution.md:13
msgid ""
"**Breaking changes are a NO.** Removing or retyping a field in a way that "
"would make existing messages invalid is rejected."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-evolution.md:16
msgid ""
"Because the judgement is structural and per-connection, one connection "
"evolving does not force every peer to upgrade in lockstep."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-evolution.md:19
msgid "The delivery handshake"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-evolution.md:21
msgid ""
"The compatibility decision is made by the **delivery handshake**. When peers "
"meet, they compare their views of a connection's contract and decide whether "
"they are compatible before traffic flows. A compatible (additive) difference "
"is accepted; an incompatible (breaking) one is refused — the same \"say NO "
"early\" principle, applied to two peers that were built against different "
"versions of the contract rather than to a single bad message."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts/contract-evolution.md:28
msgid ""
"This is why you can evolve a running system additively with confidence: the "
"handshake, not luck, decides that an old subscriber and a newer publisher "
"still agree."
msgstr ""

